<section id="higuchi-interview" class="level3">
<h3>Higuchi interview</h3>
<p><code>Higuchi:</code> When I watched the preview screening, it was [the Asuka possession scene] that shocked me the most. The scene was supposed to be cruel, with Asuka becoming â€œcorrodedâ€ and losing her face, but the [final] treatment had become incredibly gentle.</p>
<p>â€” In the first scenario, her fortune was to be pierced by a number of ultra-fine needles.</p>
<p><code>Higuchi:</code> So it was like the image of a â€œhedgehogâ€. The fact that the needles were directed towards the interior meant that Asuka was becoming intropunitive [self-punishing].</p>
<p>â€” Therefore the scenario unfolds with Kaworuâ€™s address: â€œItâ€™s not like youâ€. In Higuchi-sanâ€™s storyboard, the detached skin also becomes a face and addresses [Asuka]. The horror resembles <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kazuo%20Umezu" title="Wikipedia: Kazuo Umezu">Kazuo Umezu</a>â€™s â€œNikumenâ€, but from what image did this â€œpeeling offâ€ come from?</p>
<p><code>Higuchi:</code> The order was, â€œsomething like â€˜<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/plastination" title="Wikipedia: plastination">plastination</a>.â€™â€</p>
<p>â€” Thatâ€™s used in <a href="http://www.japantimes.co.jp/text/fl20060521x2.html" title="FATAL ATTRACTION: Vision from the other side">â€œMysteries of the Human Bodyâ€</a><a href="#fn31" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref31"><sup>31</sup></a>. Dissected, three-dimensional objects made by pouring resin into donated bodies, right?</p>
<p><code>Higuchi:</code> Right. Here, I was thinking only of something that people would hate. Up to then there had been a somewhat â€œpoka-pokaâ€ mood. Thinking â€œthis â€˜homeroom dramaâ€™ is not Eva!â€, I wanted to confront [the audience] with something hateful. In actuality, from the point of view of the story, from that point on â€œhellâ€ begins and that sort of happiness does not endure. â€œEvaâ€ is really like this; that â€œpoka-pokaâ€ atmosphere will descend into chaos! I put that sort of feeling of ill-will into my drawing.</p>
<p>When that sort of shocking thing didnâ€™t happen, I thought that the development by which the happiness that had [been portrayed] up to that point changes to tragedy probably wouldnâ€™t occur. As for the Asuka of â€œBreakâ€, it was a situation where the entire team was at odds. This being the case, I thought this [scene?] was an absolute â€œdeath flagâ€. I thought about a cruelty worse than death, and this was the result.</p>
<p>â€” I thought that this â€œâ€˜Nikumenâ€™ versionâ€ had been selected [to be used]. It was also used in Tsurumaki-sanâ€™s storyboards, and during the recording sessions I have a memory of it being recorded.</p>
<p><code>Higuchi:</code> As for when and how it was changed, I donâ€™t know, but probably the malice [I felt] when I drew the scene was too much for people to see up front.</p>
<p><a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=404501#404501">http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=404501#404501</a></p>
