<section id="excerpt-1" class="level3">
<h3>Excerpt 1</h3>
<p><a href="http://evazone.org/AME/CRC/enokido1.png">http://evazone.org/AME/CRC/enokido1.png</a></p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> Because â€œRebuild of Evangelionâ€ is basically a reconstruction of the TV series, we presume that sooner or later Rei II will die. If Shinji-kun were to save Rei II it would mean a significant departure from the TV series. However, I believed that the last scene of the film had to be an earth-shattering climax. When I had this idea, it was impossible for me not to communicate it. I remember, on the third day [of the sessions], performing a solo play in front of everyone using hand gestures and body movements entitled â€œthis is how it ends!â€</p>
<p>â€” So, in this play, you performed actions like [Shinji] pulling [Rei] up and out [of the Angel]?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> Right. Rei gets completely absorbed by the Angel. Itâ€™s just as though she has died and entered the netherworld. The audience is thinking that Rei is dead. Despite this, Shinji pilots Unit-01 again in order to save Rei. He cries out â€œAyanami!â€ and reaches forward, with an awful noise, through the front of the entry plug. He must establish some means of descending to the underworld. Finally, having grabbed (the unclothed) Reiâ€™s hand, he pulls her out with a sudden movement. I feel I demonstrated this method of rescue with all my might. I completely transformed into Shinji. I think everyone was staring at me very coldly (laugh).</p>
</section>
<section id="excerpt-2" class="level3">
<h3>Excerpt 2</h3>
<p><a href="http://img10.imageshack.us/img10/9607/enokido2.png">http://img10.imageshack.us/img10/9607/enokido2.png</a></p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> â€¦ I felt the development of the second half of the TV series was incredible. Only, I was a little saddened by death of Rei II and her replacement by Rei III. For myself, I wanted that Rei who had repeatedly shared battles and encounters with Shinji to go on to the end. But the original scenario for â€œBreakâ€ was, naturally, similar to the TV series, with Rei II self-destructing. On the morning of the third day [the production team] stayed together, I suddenly had the thought: â€œWhat if, in the final scene, Shinji happened to save Rei? â€¦ It would be incredible!â€ I worked myself up into a frenzy. Among the reasons for my enthusiasm was the recognition that this would completely overturn the expectations of the audience. When we speak of the most important â€œcatharsisâ€ provided by film, we might say that a film creates in the audience a sense that the characters are in danger, only to overturn it: we go from, â€œthis character is in danger and surely will be badly hurt,â€ to â€œit canâ€™t be!â€ This constitutes, so to speak, a betrayal of the audience in the form of a sudden change. This â€œsalvationâ€ is the essence of the final scene.</p>
</section>
<section id="excerpt-3" class="level3">
<h3>Excerpt 3</h3>
<p><a href="http://img833.imageshack.us/img833/7826/enokido3.png">http://img833.imageshack.us/img833/7826/enokido3.png</a></p>
<p>[Note: I couldnâ€™t quite work out the complete meaning of the first two sentences of this part without knowing the question Enokido was asked, so I left them out. They seem to relate to Anno and his assistant Todoroki â€œtaking overâ€ the concept.]</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> â€¦ At that time I had only decided that Shinji would save Rei II. Afterwards, as I was performing and speaking more or less off the top of my head, I was entering a kind of trance state. As is typical of me, when I reached the climactic scene where [Shinji] cries â€œAyanami!â€ and begins to walk forward, just as I grabbed [Reiâ€™s] hand and pulled [her] upwards, I suddenly came back to myself (laugh). â€œNow what happens?â€ I wondered. Now, in the film, when Shinji saves Rei, Kaworu-kun suddenly descends from heaven and impales him with a spear. When I was enthusiastically performing the â€œsavingâ€ scene, I couldnâ€™t envision anything except Kaworu-kun stabbing me with something sharp and screaming â€œThatâ€™s Enough! Act Responsibly!â€ (laugh)</p>
</section>
