<section id="part-1-1" class="level3">
<h3>Part 1</h3>
<p><a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=399646#399646">http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=399646#399646</a></p>
<blockquote>
<p>A Request to Perfect the Screenplay</p>
</blockquote>
<p>â€” We received a strong demand from Anno-san that an interview with Enokido-san be included in the â€œComplete Works Collectionâ€.</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> I see! If thatâ€™s the case, Iâ€™ll answer enthusiastically (laughs).</p>
<p>â€” When we were gathering information from (Kazuya) Tsurumaki-san before the premiere, he told us that, in â€œdestroyingâ€ Eva, your ideas are being incorporated everywhere<a href="#fn32" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref32"><sup>32</sup></a>. So weâ€™re interested [to talk to you]. Do you remember the first occasion when [Anno] reached out to consult you?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> The document [produced as a result] still exists, so I brought it.</p>
<p>â€” Thank you. The story of the exact moment contains a strange â€œpatternâ€, right?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> It was two years ago, so I think there are parts Iâ€™ve started to forget. The first talk was in 2007, I think in late September or in October.</p>
<p>â€” So just following the premiere of â€œPreludeâ€?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> Yeah. I went to see the movie, as a fan, soon after it opened. As I watched the preview trailer after the ending, I thought, â€œSo, from the next film forward we get new developments? This seems interestingâ€.</p>
<p>â€” You saw it as â€œa complete outsiderâ€, right? (smiles)</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> That night I received a call from â€œKhara-sanâ€ [Anno]. â€œWhat do you want to do for the second film?â€ â€œHuh? Me?â€ I remember a conversation along those lines.</p>
<p>â€” The fact that you had seen the first film just before that â€¦ it seems predestined, right? How did you view it?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> It was very interesting. I think it was a kind of conformation. To this day I still havenâ€™t asked [Anno], but I wondered, â€œwhy choose me for â€˜Breakâ€™â€? I thought it was either because of my collaborations with Tsurumaki-san on <em>FLCL</em> and <em>Gunbuster 2</em>, or else I had been called because of my contributions to the scripts of the original â€œEvaâ€ series as a rotating staff member.</p>
<p>â€” When we were conducting other interviews, we got the feeling that the project reached a â€œlimitâ€, followed by some kind of major change. It seems like Enokido-sanâ€™s ideas were relied on more than what had been developed previously.</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> When I was called, there were already scheduling pressures. At that time I also heard that two different versions of the last scene had been storyboarded and scrapped.</p>
<p>â€” That being the case, did you have the impression of seeing things from completely outside of the â€œRebuildâ€ project?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> Yes. Because I worked as a scriptwriter on four episodes of the original TV series, I am credited in the â€œRebuildâ€ films as a â€œscreenplay consultantâ€. However, I did no work at all on â€œPreludeâ€, and at the time I was called to work on â€œBreakâ€, a complete draft of the filmâ€™s script already existed. As Anno said he wanted further changes, I was sent a copy of the script before a meeting between us was even arranged. So first of all I read the script, and found it very interesting.</p>
<p>â€” What sort of things seemed interesting?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> To begin with, considering that â€œPreludeâ€ has to recreate episodes one through six in less than two hours, I think they did an excellent job organizing the film and maintaining balance. The story development is the same; itâ€™s okay if they crowd out the details. That being the case, when I thought about â€œBreakâ€, I expected that they would do a good job if they managed to cover episodes eight to thirteen or so. But when I realized they were attempting to treat everything up to episode twenty-three in one go, I couldnâ€™t understand how they would do it. However, when I read the script, I saw how amazingly skillfully things had been organized. â€œJust as I expected!â€ I thought. â€œIndeed, if they do it like this, the entire series becomes a single episodeâ€.</p>
<p>â€” And yet, despite doing so well, they had lost their bearings, and asked you to fix things?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> Rightâ€¦ I had received the impression that Mariâ€™s character development was not yet complete. Furthermore, I think that there were parts that still retained the atmosphere of a â€œsummary filmâ€. Because an outside observer often sees further than the participants, I thought it would be good to begin by pointing out these sorts of things. I wrote an entire â€œplan of organizationâ€ or â€œplan of revisionâ€; I believe it was this document here (Dated October 13; reproduced in CRC 2.0 pp.Â 236-237). To the extent it discusses the plot no changes are made; itâ€™s a â€œcompositional memoâ€. I submitted the memo shortly after the script arrived, and after that a meeting was arranged, but the location was not Khara-sanâ€™s studio. I was ordered, â€œCome to Atami!â€ and I was led away as though I were being abducted. Itâ€™s as one expects from â€œEvaâ€, right? (laugh)</p>
<p>â€” That was the â€œAtami Retreatâ€, right?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> When I asked, â€œWhy Atami?â€ I was answered, â€œIf we are to arrange a proper meeting, we should go where the food is deliciousâ€. Thatâ€™s a very Anno-like proposal. As the script had already been written, there were not supposed to be any major changes, and so I had thought that when I sent the memo, that would be it. When we began the â€œAtami Retreatâ€ on October 31st, I was wondering what on earth was going on.</p>
