<section id="part-2-1" class="level3">
<h3>Part 2</h3>
<p><a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=400206#400206">http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=400206#400206</a></p>
<blockquote>
<p>The Overpowering Characters of Rei and Asuka</p>
</blockquote>
<p>â€” So big changes were being intended at Atami.</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> The truth is, the day before I went to Atami, I received a call from (Toshimichi) Otsuki-san, and I was told that they would leave the content alone, and there was only one matter they wanted to pursue. At that time, based on the current screenplay, the film was projected to run between 130 and 140 minutes, and the aim was to reduce it to less than 120.</p>
<p>â€” Besides yourself, who were the members of the retreat?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> There were the directors, Anno-san, Tsurumaki-san, and Masayuki-san, as well as (Ikki) Todoroki-san, who was performing secretarial duties.</p>
<p>â€” So you begin the Atami Retreat with the assumption that you would be deepening Mariâ€™s character a little and fine-tuning the screenplay to reduce the length of the film, but what was the reality?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> Concerning the matter of strengthening Mariâ€™s character, Anno-san had already been asking me if I had any ideas, so I started to investigate the problem. However, as I worked through it, the twosome â€œRei and Asukaâ€ was such a powerful combination that they seemed to stand in the way. When I tried to investigate what made this pair so strong, I realized that this combination followed the archetype of the so called â€œharem animeâ€, and that all the desires, lusts, and dreams of young men were bound up in them.</p>
<p>One â€œtypeâ€ is the girl who was a childhood friend, who has always been with you since you were born, and with whom there are no new or strange feelings. Rei is established to resemble a â€œmotherâ€ in some respects, and so she produces in young men a feeling of distance [from things?] as though they were still half in the womb.<a href="#fn33" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref33"><sup>33</sup></a> Now, Asukaâ€™s particular type is that of the girl who comes from a foreign country. This also produces a very good feeling. Probably it is the male instinct to think, in some respects, that girls from another world are better than girls who are familiar and close to hand (laughs).</p>
<p>â€” Certainly, if we assume that there is a male instinct to â€œspreadâ€ DNA, or propagate the species by mixing heterogeneous elements.</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> The sadness and happiness of young men is bound up in the fact that they always possess these two contradictory wishes. The so-called â€œHarem Animeâ€ genre is for the most part intended to satisfy these desires. In â€œUrusei Yatsuraâ€, Shinobu is the Japanese girl who was oneâ€™s childhood friend and always by oneâ€™s side, and Lum is the â€œalien girlâ€. We say â€œalienâ€, but [such characters] perhaps [have] an â€œAmericanâ€ image. Rei and Asuka exactly fit the pattern of this â€œperfect lineupâ€.</p>
<p>Now, coming up with a plan as regards the third girl who must compete with this â€œultimate combinationâ€ seemed to me a very difficult job. In addition, Director Anno had not, up to this point, developed anything himself, but, expressing the desire for a completely new character, had left Mariâ€™s development to others.</p>
<p>This being the case, my first proposal for an additional type was a Sapphire (from [Tezuka Osamuâ€™s] <em>Princess Knight</em>) type. If Rei and Asuka are completely different types, I wondered if a â€œneutralâ€, lighthearted type who battles with an â€œinnocentâ€ image would be good. At this point, though Anno-san agreed that it would be good, he thought a Wato (Chiyoko) type (from [Tezukaâ€™s] <em>The Three-Eyed One</em>) would be more realistic, and he got quite excited about it.</p>
<p>However, Tsurumaki-san, who had been listening nearby, was looking at us with a distant expression. It looked as though he was thinking, â€œItâ€™s a pleasant conversation [for you], but just who is going to be saddled with the difficulty of placing that character in the world of Eva?â€ (laughs) I think the result of finalizing Mariâ€™s appeal was that Tsurumaki-san was made to suffer with storyboards.</p>
<p>â€” Since viewers were heavily anticipating a new character from the first filmâ€™s preview, you want to give Mari more to do; was that the atmosphere [at Atami]?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> As we had many conversations relating to Mari, I think it was. As for other images, there was the part of a Miko-san [shrine maiden] channeling the gods. She is not â€œpracticalâ€ like Asuka, but thinks about â€œdeepâ€ things, like someone who somehow can see mysterious things like those connected with the gods. She is not â€œunworldlyâ€ to Reiâ€™s extent and she talks a lot. As nothing had yet solidified, we had these sorts of discussions about ideas.</p>
<p>â€” I have a feeling that those ideas influenced the final film. What other discussions did you have about Mari?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> We didnâ€™t just discuss her character traits, but we were also tangled up in discussing to what extent she should appear in the film. I remember that this caused everyone a great deal of distress. If we wanted to increase her appearances we could, but, because we were limited by the running time of the film, the number of scenes depicting the activity of other characters would be reduced. Even watching the completed film, there are selections we made at the last minute. If we added more Mari, we would have to further cut strong scenes involving Rei and Asuka, but if we didnâ€™t, then there would have been no point to putting Mari in the second film [to begin with]. In the end I think we were impressed with her character and have high expectations for her in the future.</p>
<p>â€” In the original scenario Mari was the daughter of a distinguished English family who kept dogs and cats, and so on; what were the circumstances [relating to that]?</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> Speaking of that, I also remember conversations like, â€œWhat if we gave her tattoos of the names of all the pets sheâ€™s kept up until now?â€ For example, we would insert a bath scene where we see the area from her chest to her stomach is completely covered in tattoos. If she gets asked, â€œWhy do you have them?â€ sheâ€™d answer something like, â€œTheyâ€™re the names of all my pets that have died up until now. The tattoos ensure I donâ€™t forget them, and that they still â€˜liveâ€™ with meâ€.</p>
<p>â€” Thatâ€™s a striking character trait.</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> Did this development survive or die off? Because Mari hasnâ€™t undressed yet, nobody knows (laughs). With things like this, we tried too hard to develop Mariâ€™s character traits; when I think back on it, we were only discussing â€œforcedâ€ or â€œabsurdâ€ things. In asking â€œhow can we beat Rei or Asuka?â€ we had a tendency to get a little bit too much into an â€œimpact contestâ€.</p>
<p>â€” After all, if you want to insert Mari somewhere, you have to leave out Rei or Asuka. We also heard about this difficulty from Tsurumaki-san.</p>
<p><code>Enokido:</code> There were versions of the unfinished screenplay where Mari appears only at the beginning, and doesnâ€™t participate in the battle at the end.</p>
