<section id="seventh-angelshigeto-koyama" class="level3">
<h3>Seventh Angel/Shigeto Koyama</h3>
<p><a href="http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=436453#436453">http://forum.evageeks.org/viewtopic.php?p=436453#436453</a></p>
<p>Rough sketches for settei/Shigeto Koyama</p>
<p>Speculations on the structure of the head, midsection, etc.</p>
<p>Directions for 3D CG model brush-up/Daizen Komatsuda (pp.Â 147-148)</p>
<p>I was called in after (Daizen) Komatsuda-sanâ€™s â€œHeiwajimaâ€ concept was OKed by Anno-san. Even beforehand, I really loved the magnificent designs of the angels, and had thought at some length about what design elements would be necessary to establish something as an angel. The impetus which enabled my answer was a â€œVira Seijinâ€ ballpoint pen I received when I visited the home of scriptwriter Yoji Enokido-san. After studying Toru Narita-sanâ€™s designs of monsters and space aliens for <em><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ultraman" title="Wikipedia: Ultraman">Ultraman</a></em> and <em><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ultra%20Seven" title="Wikipedia: Ultra Seven">Ultra Seven</a></em>, I noticed [he used] a sculptural design: a â€œlinearâ€, â€œgeometricalâ€ shape consisting of â€œsurfacesâ€ with depth. [*]</p>
<p>Moreover, when I worked on director Tsurumaki-sanâ€™s <em>Aim for the Top 2!</em> [<em>Diebuster</em>], I personally wanted to make an effort to link the designs [of that work] to those of Anno-sanâ€™s prior work, <em>Aim for the Top!</em> [<em>Gunbuster</em>], so I thoroughly studied â€œAnno designâ€ and â€œAnno detailâ€ by looking at settei and individual frames [from that work]. Because of that experience, I was able to grasp that the disposition of triangles and hexagons was a crucial element [of Annoâ€™s design]. [*]</p>
<p>As a result, I considered there to be two design requirements for an angel: the design should be â€œsculpturalâ€ and â€œcontain triangles and hexagons.â€ Furthermore, I suggested a third requirement: â€œits actions exceed human reason.â€ The idea that its floating feet would seem to â€œrendâ€ the air like â€œdividersâ€, [?] leave tracks of ice, and walk upon the surface of the water was [for the sake of] this third, â€œbehavioralâ€ requirement. I found Komatsuda-sanâ€™s â€œHeiwajimaâ€ concept<a href="#fn118" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref118"><sup>118</sup></a> personally interesting, [â€¦]<a href="#fn119" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref119"><sup>119</sup></a></p>
<p>Furthermore, Anno-san brought up the image of the Toshiba IHI pavilion at Osaka <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expo%20%2770" title="Wikipedia: Expo '70">Expo â€™70</a><a href="#fn120" class="footnoteRef" id="fnref120"><sup>120</sup></a> (designed by Kisho Kurokawa) - I was thinking, â€œThe tetra-frame is a polygon! At last!â€ and was privately delighted (laughs). So, I submitted a rough design showing a hexagonal shape comprised of tetra-frames, and [the idea] was OKed.</p>
<p>For the face, I submitted various patterns along the lines of a design by Yoshito Asari-san, the â€œinorganicâ€, â€œexpressionless,â€ â€œegolessâ€ character of which inspired dread. [*] The new designs of the provisional Unit-05 and the third angel during the pre-title sequence would, as the opening strike, surprise the viewers, so I thought that there should be an angel design which could reassure the viewers a bit, like, â€œwithout doubt, this is Eva!â€ I decided upon the colors - black and white, with red mixed in - using the same rationale. At the stage where the face was decided, an idea of Anno-sanâ€™s - â€œit should move like a clock, â€˜kaku, kakuâ€™â€ - was incorporated. We converted the confirmed image into a 3D model. What we made adjustments to on the monitor became the final design.</p>
